\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing onehalf
\noindent
A sandy, steep coast or shelf is build up from sandy material.
 Sand in small grain size of down to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.0025-0.0049in$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $62.5-125\text{µm}$
\end_inset

) is a very fine sand (mud, silt and clay is even finer).
 The sand particles are packed and perfectly aligned and the inter space
 allows only freshwater to pass trough.
 Permeability of such a system allows the water particles to diffuse but
 as salty particles are too big, they stay out.
 This brings a grade of salinity in front of the sand barrier.
 If the sandy material experiences a movement in pressure shift within the
 constructed system, the salinity gradient in front would fall due to freshwater
 inflow from the sandy system.
 A stationary monitoring system could permanently check the salinity in
 front of the sand barrier while an AUV drives by every now and then to
 check the whole site for optical changes and chemical differences as well
 as also salinity for reference reasons.
\end_layout

